Each model is about 45 cm ( 18 in ) tall and was created using a polystyrene or cardboard core with knitting sewn on Each model is about 45 cm (18 in) tall and was created using a polystyrene or cardboard core with knitting sewn on. This ambitious Dolphin Women's Institute project aimed to capture Braintree's unique character through miniature landmarks. Initiated during lockdowns, it offered members a creative outlet and shared goal. Led by talented Elaine Pye, a long-standing member and avid knitter, the group focused on iconic structures defining Braintree's heritage. Beyond the meticulously crafted church and museum, other notable additions include the historic town hall, vibrant market square, and a miniature old railway station, each brought to life with incredible detail. The intricate process involved members dedicating countless hours to knitting specific textures and colours for each building's facade, windows, and roofs. Completed knitted sections were then carefully cut and sewn onto prepared cores, ensuring a perfect fit and realistic appearance. The precision for these miniature architectural marvels is truly impressive. Elaine Pye, known for her intricate textile art, guided the team through challenging aspects, sharing techniques and encouraging collaborative work. This dedication has resulted in a unique exhibition celebrating both the town's history and the incredible crafting skills within the Dolphin Women's Institute. The completed collection is set to be displayed at various community events and local venues across Braintree throughout the coming months, starting with an inaugural viewing at the Braintree Museum. This public display will allow residents and visitors alike to appreciate the intricate workmanship and recognise their beloved town in a brand new, whimsical format. The project has fostered community among WI members and generated considerable local interest, drawing praise for its originality and charm. The Dolphin Women's Institute hopes this unique collection will inspire others, serving as a delightful testament to their creativity and commitment to enriching local life. While primarily focused on Braintree, the project's success has even garnered attention from neighbouring WI groups, with some Hertfordshire members expressing interest in similar initiatives.

For the first time, MPs have agreed in a vote that we will begin the process of leaving the EU by the end of March.
The government chief whip was seen with a massive grin after tonight's vote.
Remember ministers' climbdown came with a clever kicker, persuading Labour to sign up to their timetable for triggering Article 50 without committing to very much in return - the vague promise of a plan that could be as detailed as the back of the proverbial fag packet.
There's grumpiness on the Labour benches at how it was handled - angry conversations taking place, sources suggest - a sense among some that the front bench allowed themselves to be hoodwinked by the government's cunning plan.
Potential Tory rebels on the Remain side are deeply suspicious of the government's real intentions for giving more information about its ideas for Brexit. They backed off today, but will be back for more, no question.
But beyond the immediate machinations and the chief whip's big grin, two realities are confirmed by the events of the last 24 hours.
Yes - the numbers tonight suggest not very many MPs will actually try to block Brexit, or frustrate the process. They will certainly try to push the government for more details. They will certainly try to amend the proposals that eventually make it to the Commons, whenever that is. That could disrupt and delay things, but trying to stop it happening is not on the agenda of the vast majority.
But what's equally clear is that Theresa May does not have a secure majority on the EU. As soon as her plans (eventually) hit the floor of the House, she's likely to have to compromise.
That is precisely why the government is fighting so hard just across the road in the Supreme Court to try to avoid MPs having a say before the really hard work in Brussels even begins.

Mr Mullholland told MSPs that further work was needed by the Police Investigations and Review Commissioner before a fatal accident inquiry could be held into Mr Bayoh's death. He explained that PIRC needed to finalise several lines of inquiry and consolidate all evidence pertaining to the incident in Kirkcaldy on 3 May. The Lord Advocate, Frank Mulholland, stressed his commitment to a robust and transparent process, assuring MSPs that justice would be diligently pursued for the family.

The family's lawyer, Aamer Anwar, while acknowledging the need for a thorough investigation, reiterated their urgent desire for the inquiry to be convened without undue delay. Mr Anwar emphasised that establishing "the truth of what happened" to Mr Bayoh in police custody remained their paramount goal, seeing the FAI as the essential mechanism for achieving this.

The fatal accident inquiry, once initiated, will meticulously examine all circumstances surrounding Mr Bayoh’s death, including the conduct of officers involved, medical care provided, and any systemic issues. Media playback is not supported on this device Kompany was instrumental as City took the lead , pressuring Giorgio Chiellini into turning the ball into his own net . However , he sustained a calf injury as the Italians fought back to win 2 - 1 . " We will have to see how Vincent is on Wednesday , " said City manager Manuel Pellegrini . " We will check and see how serious the injury is . " Kompany , 29 , was replaced by Nicolas Otamendi - City 's £32 million summer signing from Valencia. The Belgium international had been in outstanding form at the start of the season, scoring two goals in four Premier League games and leading a defence that had not conceded a single goal prior to Tuesday’s Champions League opener. His forced withdrawal against Juventus is a significant blow for Manuel Pellegrini’s side, especially given Kompany’s history of calf problems. The City captain has been plagued by similar injuries throughout his career, leading to concerns about his long-term availability.

Pellegrini expressed his immediate worry in the post-match media briefing, acknowledging the severity of losing such a pivotal player. "It's a very important injury for Vincent," he reiterated. "He was playing very well and we hope it's not a serious one. We will know more after he has a scan." The manager also confirmed that Sergio Aguero, who had been substituted in the first half of Saturday's Premier League win over Crystal Palace, was not fit enough to feature against the Italians. The absence of both Kompany and Aguero highlights the squad depth challenges that City might face as they navigate a demanding schedule of domestic and European fixtures. The team’s strong start to the Premier League season has built high expectations, and maintaining that momentum will require all players to stay fit and perform.

The defensive partnership between Kompany and Otamendi was one that City fans were eager to see develop, with the Argentine having been eased into the squad. Now, Otamendi is likely to be thrust into a starting role much sooner than anticipated, potentially alongside Eliaquim Mangala or Martin Demichelis. The loss to Juventus, despite Kompany's early influence in pressuring Giorgio Chiellini for the own goal, marked a disappointing start to City’s Champions League campaign. The focus will now shift to how Pellegrini reshapes his defence and inspires a response from his team in the upcoming derby against Manchester United. The media will undoubtedly scrutinize City’s defensive performance in the absence of their influential captain, Vincent Kompany, as they aim to bounce back from this early European setback and continue their impressive domestic form.

Andreea Cristea is the fifth victim of the attack on 22 March, in which Khalid Masood drove into crowds on Westminster Bridge then stabbed a policeman to death, before being shot dead himself.
Ms Cristea, 31, who was on holiday with boyfriend Andrei Burnaz, had been in hospital since the attack.
It has emerged that Mr Burnaz had been planning to propose during the day out.
A family statement confirmed Ms Cristea, who was an architect, had died on Thursday.
The family said: "After fighting for her life for over two weeks, our beloved and irreplaceable Andreea - wonderful daughter, sister, partner, dedicated friend and the most unique and life loving person you can imagine - was cruelly and brutally ripped away from our lives in the most heartless and spiritless way.
"She will always be remembered as our shining ray of light that will forever keep on shining in our hearts."
The family said they were "deeply touched and eternally grateful" to the "never-ending dedication" of the medical staff who treated Ms Cristea, saying their "kindness and empathy are beyond compare".
"There are no words to even begin to describe the crushing pain and emptiness that is left in our hearts," they continued.
Mr Burnaz, who sustained a broken foot in the attack, visited Westminster Bridge last week to lay a single white rose.
The couple were in London to celebrate Mr Burnaz's birthday and he had been planning to propose to Ms Cristea that day, Romania's UK ambassador Dan Mihalache told the BBC.
He said it was thought Masood's car had mounted the pavement and hit Mr Burnaz, before pushing Ms Cristea into the Thames.

Project manager Greg Thornett said: "We uncovered the footings for the former platforms while we were preparing the top of the viaduct for new track and we are now working up in the roof space of the former ticket hall to fill in the old skylights, ready to carry the final track alignment.

The statement from the firm came just days after it announced the sale of the Financial Times to Japan 's Nikkei . Pearson said it was in discussions regarding the sale of the Economist but there was " no certainty that this process will lead to a transaction ". This divestment of its print media holdings, including the iconic Financial Times, signals a clear strategic pivot for Pearson. The company, under CEO John Fallon, is increasingly focusing on its global education business, aiming to streamline its portfolio and concentrate resources on digital learning and assessment tools. This marks the end of an era for Pearson as a diversified media conglomerate, aligning with a broader industry trend of specialization.

The potential sale of its 50% stake in the Economist Group, which publishes the influential weekly magazine, presents a more intricate challenge. Unlike the straightforward acquisition of the Financial Times by Japan's Nikkei, the Economist has a unique ownership structure designed to safeguard its editorial independence. A trust holds a significant portion of shares, and a consortium of long-standing family shareholders – including the Rothschilds, Cadburys, and Schroders, alongside Italy's powerful Agnelli family through their investment vehicle Exor – own the remaining stakes. John Elkann, chairman of Exor, had publicly expressed interest in increasing their shareholding, emphasizing their commitment to maintaining the publication's journalistic integrity and distinct ethos.

This inherent complexity, requiring consensus among existing shareholders deeply invested in the Economist's long-term vision, explains Pearson's cautious statement regarding "no certainty." For Pearson, completing these divestitures would solidify its identity as a pure-play education company, allowing it to dedicate all efforts to developing digital learning platforms globally and capitalize on the evolving education sector. These moves underscore the significant redefinition underway in the media and publishing industries.

RamJam uploaded Southern Rail Tycoon on Thursday , and so far 45,000 people have played the tongue - in - cheek game . The aim is to stop guards from boarding trains , which leads to services being cancelled as profits are collected from passengers . It was inspired by months of cancellations due to an RMT dispute . Once a sufficient number of train guards board on a train and a delayed service eventually departs , the player loses the round, and is presented with a screen showing plummeting profits and irate pixelated commuters storming a virtual London Victoria station. The game, created by Brighton-based indie developer Tom Jackson, under his studio moniker RamJam, has rapidly become a viral sensation. Jackson, a long-time frustrated commuter on the Southern Rail network himself, explained the inspiration behind the satirical hit: 'I spent so many hours delayed on platforms, watching those departure boards mock me, that I just had to channel that frustration into something. It started as a joke among friends, but the more I worked on 'Southern Rail Tycoon', the more I realised how many people could relate to the sheer absurdity of it all.'

The game’s dark humour resonates deeply with those who have endured the real-life chaos on the network. Players must strategically deploy various humorous obstacles, from ‘broken signal’ alerts to ‘leaf on the line’ incidents, all designed to prevent guards from reaching their designated carriages. The more services cancelled, the higher the player's 'tycoon' score, reflecting their fictional mastery over the beleaguered railway. If too many services depart on time, or if guards successfully board multiple trains, the player's 'profit margin' collapses, leading to a swift game over.

Despite its cynical premise, Tom Jackson insists the game is not meant to be a serious political statement, but rather a cathartic outlet. 'It’s about making light of a difficult situation,' he stated. 'It’s satire. It’s a way for people to laugh at the chaos, rather than just fuming about it. We’ve had messages from people in London, Brighton, and all along the line saying how much they appreciate being able to turn their anger into amusement, even if it’s just for a few minutes.' RamJam is now considering updates to Southern Rail Tycoon, including new scenarios and 'disaster' events, as well as a potential mobile version, cementing its status as a cult classic for exasperated commuters everywhere.

The study tracked more than 200,000 Australian smokers and non - smokers above the age of 45 over six years . Mortality risk went up with cigarette use , BMC Medicine reports . Smoking 10 cigarettes a day doubled the risk , while 20 - a - day smokers were four to five times more likely to die . Although someone who smokes could lead a long life , their habit makes this less likely . Smoking increases the risk of a multitude of health problems, including various cancers, cardiovascular diseases, and respiratory illnesses. The study, published in BMC Medicine, underscored the profound impact of even moderate smoking on mortality rates, reinforcing decades of research on the dangers of tobacco. Lung cancer is perhaps the most well-known consequence, but smoking also significantly elevates the risk of cancers of the throat, mouth, oesophagus, bladder, kidney, pancreas, stomach, and cervix, as well as acute myeloid leukaemia. Beyond cancer, smokers are at a much higher risk of heart attacks, strokes, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), emphysema, and bronchitis. It also contributes to conditions like type 2 diabetes, age-related macular degeneration (leading to blindness), and osteoporosis, weakening bones.

Prof Emily Banks, a leading researcher involved in the BMC Medicine study, emphasised that "Even smoking a few cigarettes a day has substantial effects on mortality." Her work, along with findings from other major health organisations, consistently points to a clear dose-response relationship between cigarette use and adverse health outcomes. Organizations such as Cancer Research UK and the American Cancer Society have long championed public health campaigns to reduce smoking rates, highlighting the preventable nature of many tobacco-related diseases. In the UK, significant progress has been made in reducing smoking prevalence, but it remains a leading cause of premature death and illness. The message from health experts is clear: quitting smoking at any age can dramatically improve health prospects and extend life, reducing the heightened risks associated with continued tobacco use. Even for long-term smokers, quitting starts a process of healing and risk reduction that can add years to one's life and improve overall quality of health. The evidence is overwhelming: every cigarette takes a toll on the body, making the decision to quit one of the most beneficial steps an individual can take for their health and well-being.
